{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473739"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:13:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:13:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2728"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2728"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.01,0.7,0.09,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2728"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107582"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2728"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2728"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90034"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"527"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"12916"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3502"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3517"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40070"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40115"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44092"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107582"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 13-year-old girl presents to the Emergency Department with her father with a 12-hour history of crampy central abdominal pain. The pain came on suddenly and has been progressively worsening. She reports nausea but has not vomited. She denies any bowel changes or urinary symptoms. She has no significant medical or surgical history and takes no regular medications. Her last menstrual period was seven days ago. She reports that she is not sexually active.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears in obvious distress but is alert and oriented. Her pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals tenderness, particularly in the right iliac fossa. There is no rebound, percussion or cross-tenderness on examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next diagnostic step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Formal bloods (CBE, EUC, LFT, CRP)","Point of care bloods (VBG)","Abdominal ultrasound","CT abdomen and pelvis","Appendicectomy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis girl\u0027s presentation of acute abdominal pain, in combination with the examination findings, supports a possible diagnosis of acute appendicitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile cases of high suspicion should be managed with early \u003Cstrong\u003Eappendicectomy\u003C/strong\u003E, in this case, where there is some diagnostic uncertainty and the child is stable, it would be appropriate to investigate further.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E remains the first-line imaging option for acute appendicitis, and although the accuracy is technician dependent, it provides a safe and cost-effective alternative to CT scanning. In 2016, Kharbanda et al developed a protocol for acute appendicitis whereby CT scanning was only used if ultrasound was unequivocal, and as a result they saw a 54% decrease in CT usage with no significant change in the rates of missed appendicitis or representation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAbdominopelvic CT radiation is associated with a higher incidence of haematologic malignant neoplasms, particularly in the paediatric population aged 0-15 years; therefore \u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen and pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E would not be an appropriate next step for this patient. CT scanning in acute appendicitis should not be discarded, however need to be medically justified and thoughtfully dose-optimised, particularly in paediatric patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormal bloods (CBE, EUC, LFT, CRP)\u003C/strong\u003E may show inflammatory markers such as elevated white cell count and C-reactive protein, but these findings are non-specific and insufficient to diagnose appendicitis. While blood tests are often part of the workup, they should not delay appropriate imaging in a patient with suspected appendicitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPoint of care bloods (VBG)\u003C/strong\u003E provides even less information than formal blood tests in this context. While it may give some basic information about electrolytes and acid-base status, it does not provide the inflammatory markers needed to support a diagnosis of appendicitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Abdominal ultrasound is the first-line imaging modality for suspected appendicitis in children due to its safety profile and absence of radiation.","CT abdomen should be used judiciously in paediatric patients due to the increased lifetime risk of radiation-induced malignancy.","Laboratory tests alone are insufficient to diagnose or exclude appendicitis in children but can support clinical assessment."],"references":["Anandalwar SP, Graham DA, Kashtan MA, Bachur RG, Barnewolt CE, Callahan MJ, et al. Leveraging the Combined Predictive Value of Ultrasound and Laboratory Data to Reduce Radiation Exposure and Resource Utilization in Children with Suspected Appendicitis. J Surg Res. 2021;257:529-36. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32919343/","Hu A, Lautz TB, Raval MV. Comments on Computed Tomography for Evaluating Appendicitis. JAMA Surg. 2021;156(11):1073-1074. Available at: https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamasurgery/article-abstract/2782153","Kharbanda AB, Madhok M, Krause E, Vazquez-Benitez G, Kharbanda EO, Mize W, et al. Implementation of Electronic Clinical Decision Support for Pediatric Appendicitis. Pediatrics. 2016;137(5):e20151745. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27244781/","Lee KH, Lee S, Park JH. Comments on Computed Tomography for Evaluating Appendicitis\u2014Reply. JAMA Surg. 2021;156(11):1073-1074. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34287619/","Lee KH, Lee S, Park JH, Lee SS, Kim HY, Lee WJ, et al. Risk of Hematologic Malignant Neoplasms From Abdominopelvic Computed Tomographic Radiation in Patients Who Underwent Appendectomy. JAMA Surg. 2021;156(4):343-51. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8047726/","Schaps D, Frush DP, Rice HE.  Comments on Computed 156(11):1073. Available at: https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamasurgery/article-abstract/2782154"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90034"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2728"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90034"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-01T09:52:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-01T09:52:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2728"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107582"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount